  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations to Arkansas total $612M in FY2026 to date, distributed across 13,109 awards with an average award size of $46.7K and a year-over-year change down 51.6%. Obligations by fiscal year show variation: FY21 $1.5B, FY22 $1.4B, FY23 $1.3B, FY24 $1.9B, FY25 $1.3B, and FY26 $612M. The Department of Defense is the largest buying agency with $377M, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs with $89.7M and the Department of State with $30.8M. Top vendors include BL HARBERT INTERNATIONAL LLC at $102M and ALBERICI CONSTRUCTORS INC at $68.2M, and contract activity concentrates in construction and engineering: Commercial and Institutional Building Construction $155M, Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction $115M, and Water and Sewer Line and Related Structures Construction $33M. Sector detail shows Computer Facilities Management Services $32.4M and All Other Miscellaneous Chemical Product and Preparation Manufacturing $30.1M. These figures reflect partial fiscal-year totals for FY2026 to date.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has federal spending in Arkansas changed recently?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 51.6% year over year, with FY26 obligations at $612M compared with FY25 $1.3B and FY24 $1.9B. Annual history shows FY21 $1.5B, FY22 $1.4B, and FY23 $1.3B, indicating FY24 was the peak in this series."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors dominate contracting in Arkansas?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense accounts for $377M of FY2026 to date obligations, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs $89.7M and the Department of State $30.8M. The largest vendors are BL HARBERT INTERNATIONAL LLC $102M and ALBERICI CONSTRUCTORS INC $68.2M, and the largest industry categories are Commercial and Institutional Building Construction $155M and Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction $115M."
      }
    ]
